ol.li: Investor: The primary user of the system, engaging in various trading and account management activities.
Broker: Possibly a secondary user or a system role that facilitates or supports transactions and activities carried out by the investor.

h3.style: font-style: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration: none; caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); color: rgb(0, 0, 0);

ol.style: font-style: normal; font-variant-caps: normal; font-weight: 400; letter-spacing: normal; orphans: auto; text-align: start; text-indent: 0px; text-transform: none; white-space: normal; widows: auto; word-spacing: 0px; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px; text-decoration: none; caret-color: rgb(0, 0, 0); color: rgb(0, 0, 0);
ol.li: Manage Account: Allows the investor to make changes to their account settings and personal details.
View Account: Investors can view the details of their accounts, including current balances, transaction history, and perhaps investment performance.
Deposit/Withdraw Funds: Enables investors to deposit money into their account or withdraw funds from it.
View Market Data: Provides real-time or near-real-time financial data to the investor, which is crucial for making informed trading decisions.
Market Analysis: Offers analytical tools or insights into market trends, which can help investors make better investment choices.
Buy Stock: Investors can purchase stocks through the platform.
Sell Stock: Investors can sell stocks they own.
Cancel Order: This use case allows investors to cancel previously placed orders that have not yet been executed.
Stock Information: This could be detailed information about specific stocks, such as historical performance, dividend yields, or company news.

How Many Shares: This might represent a feature where investors can query the number of shares available for a particular stock or how many they can afford based on their account balance and the stock's current price.

ul.li: Association: There are likely lines connecting actors to use cases, indicating which actor can perform which use cases. For example, both "Investor" and "Broker" might be connected to "View Market Data", suggesting both can use this feature.

Include/Extend (if applicable): There might be relationships indicating that some use cases are mandatory for others (include) or optional (extend). For example, "View Account" might include "View Market Data", or "Buy Stock" might extend "View Market Data", suggesting additional, optional functionalities.
